[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] In programming language theory, **lazy evaluation**, or **call-by-need**, is an evaluation strategy which delays the evaluation of an expression until its value is needed (non-strict evaluation) and which avoids repeated evaluations (by the use of sharing).
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] Lazy evaluation is often combined with memoization, as described in Jon Bentley's *Writing Efficient Programs*.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] If so, the stored result is simply returned.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] If not, the function is evaluated, and another entry is added to the lookup table for reuse.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] Lazy evaluation is difficult to combine with imperative features such as exception handling and input/output, because the order of operations becomes indeterminate.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] The opposite of lazy evaluation is eager evaluation, sometimes known as strict evaluation.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] Eager evaluation is the evaluation strategy employed in most programming languages.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] Lazy evaluation was introduced for lambda calculus by Christopher Wadsworth.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] For programming languages, it was independently introduced by Peter Henderson and James H.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] Delayed evaluation is used particularly in functional programming languages.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] When using delayed evaluation, an expression is not evaluated as soon as it gets bound to a variable, but when the evaluator is forced to produce the expression's value.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] Lazy evaluation is fundamental in big data frameworks such as Apache Spark, where computations on distributed datasets are delayed until results are explicitly needed, allowing for execution optimizations and reduction of unnecessary processing.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] Lazy evaluation allows control structures to be defined normally, and not as primitives or compile-time techniques.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] These have the usual semantics, i.e., `ifThenElse a b c` evaluates (a), then if and only if (a) evaluates to true does it evaluate (b), otherwise it evaluates (c).
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] That is, exactly one of (b) or (c) will be evaluated.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] Similarly, for `EasilyComputed || LotsOfWork`, if the easy part gives **True** the lots of work expression could be avoided.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] Finally, when evaluating `SafeToTry && Expression`, if *SafeToTry* is **false** there will be no attempt at evaluating the *Expression*.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] Conversely, in an eager language the above definition for `ifThenElse a b c` would evaluate (a), (b), and (c) regardless of the value of (a).
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] This is not the desired behavior, as (b) or (c) may have side effects, take a long time to compute, or throw errors.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] It is usually possible to introduce user-defined lazy control structures in eager languages as functions, though they may depart from the language's syntax for eager evaluation: Often the involved code bodies need to be wrapped in a function value, so that they are executed only when called.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] Delayed evaluation has the advantage of being able to create calculable infinite lists without infinite loops or size matters interfering in computation.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] The actual values are only computed when needed.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] For example, one could create a function that creates an infinite list (often called a *stream*) of Fibonacci numbers.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] The calculation of the *n*-th Fibonacci number would be merely the extraction of that element from the infinite list, forcing the evaluation of only the first n members of the list.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] In the function numberFromInfiniteList, the value of infinity is an infinite range, but until an actual value (or more specifically, a specific value at a certain index) is needed, the list is not evaluated, and even then, it is only evaluated as needed (i.e., only to the desired index).
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] Provided the programmer is careful, the program completes normally.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] In Haskell syntax, "`:`" prepends an element to a list, `tail` returns a list without its first element, and `zipWith` uses a specified function (in this case addition) to combine corresponding elements of two lists to produce a third.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] In computer windowing systems, the painting of information to the screen is driven by *expose events* which drive the display code at the last possible moment.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] By doing this, windowing systems avoid computing unnecessary display content updates.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] Another example of laziness in modern computer systems is copy-on-write page allocation or demand paging, where memory is allocated only when a value stored in that memory is changed.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] Laziness can be useful for high performance scenarios.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] An example is the Unix mmap function, which provides *demand driven* loading of pages from disk, so that only those pages actually touched are loaded into memory, and unneeded memory is not allocated.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] MATLAB implements *copy on edit*, where arrays which are copied have their actual memory storage replicated only when their content is changed, possibly leading to an *out of memory* error when updating an element afterwards instead of during the copy operation.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] The number of beta reductions to reduce a lambda term with call-by-need is not larger than the number needed by call-by-value or call-by-name reduction.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] Call-by-need embodies two optimizations - never repeat work (similar to call-by-value), and never perform unnecessary work (similar to call-by-name).
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] Lazy evaluation can also lead to reduction in memory footprint, since values are created when needed.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] In practice, lazy evaluation may cause significant performance issues compared to eager evaluation.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] For example, on modern computer architectures, delaying a computation and performing it later is slower than performing it immediately .
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] This can be alleviated through strictness analysis.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] Lazy evaluation can also introduce memory leaks due to unevaluated expressions.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] Some programming languages delay evaluation of expressions by default, and some others provide functions or special syntax to delay evaluation.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] In KRC, Miranda, and Haskell, evaluation of function arguments is delayed by default.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] In many other languages, evaluation can be delayed by explicitly suspending the computation using special syntax (as with Scheme's "`delay`" and "`force`" and OCaml's "`lazy`" and "`Lazy.force`") or, more generally, by wrapping the expression in a thunk.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] In lazy programming languages such as Haskell, although the default is to evaluate expressions only when they are demanded, it is possible in some cases to make code more eager—or conversely, to make it more lazy again after it has been made more eager.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] This can be done by explicitly coding something which forces evaluation (which may make the code more eager) or avoiding such code (which may make the code more lazy).
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] *Strict* evaluation usually implies eagerness, but they are technically different concepts.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] However, there is an optimisation implemented in some compilers called strictness analysis, which, in some cases, allows the compiler to infer that a value will always be used.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] In such cases, this may render the programmer's choice of whether to force that particular value or not, irrelevant, because strictness analysis will force strict evaluation.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] In Haskell, marking constructor fields strict means that their values will always be demanded immediately.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] The `seq` function can also be used to demand a value immediately and then pass it on, which is useful if a constructor field should generally be lazy.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] However, neither of these techniques implements *recursive* strictness—for that, a function called `deepSeq` was invented.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] Also, pattern matching in Haskell 98 is strict by default, so the `~` qualifier has to be used to make it lazy.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] In C++, the `std::ranges` library uses lazy range adaptors.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] In Java, lazy evaluation can be done by using objects that have a method to evaluate them when the value is needed.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] The body of this method must contain the code required to perform this evaluation.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] Since the introduction of lambda expressions in Java SE8, Java has supported a compact notation for this.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] The `Lazy` interface with its `eval()` method is equivalent to the `Supplier` interface with its `get()` method in the `java.util.function` library.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] Each class that implements the `Lazy` interface must provide an `eval` method, and instances of the class may carry whatever values the method needs to accomplish lazy evaluation.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] In the above, the variable a initially refers to a lazy integer object created by the lambda expression `() -> 1`.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] Evaluating this lambda expression is similar to constructing a new instance of an anonymous class that implements `Lazy<Integer>` with an eval method returning 1.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] Each iteration of the loop links a to a new object created by evaluating the lambda expression inside the loop.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] Each of these objects holds a reference to another lazy object, b, and has an eval method that calls `b.eval()` twice and returns the sum.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] The variable b is needed here to meet Java's requirement that variables referenced from within a lambda expression be effectively final.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] This is an inefficient program because this implementation of lazy integers does not memoize the result of previous calls to eval.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] It also involves considerable autoboxing and unboxing.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] What may not be obvious is that, at the end of the loop, the program has constructed a linked list of 11 objects and that all of the actual additions involved in computing the result are done in response to the call to `a.eval()` on the final line of code.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] This call recursively traverses the list to perform the necessary additions.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] This allows the previous example to be rewritten to be far more efficient.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] Java's lambda expressions are just syntactic sugar.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] In JavaScript, lazy evaluation can be simulated by using a generator.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] You can run this example yourself by going to the Kotlin Playground.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] To verify that the program lazily loaded `isThePizzaReady` instead of initializing it beforehand as true we need to check the output of the program.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] As we can see when the program reads from `isThePizzaReady` it prints out a statement we put inside the lazy code block on line 4.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] The statement on line 4 does not execute more than once.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] In Python 2.x the `range()` function computes a list of integers.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] In Python 3.x the `range()` function returns a generator which computes elements of the list on demand.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] This change to lazy evaluation saves execution time for large ranges which may never be fully referenced and memory usage for large ranges where only one or a few elements are needed at any time.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] In Python 2.x is possible to use a function called `xrange()` which returns an object that generates the numbers in the range on demand.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] The advantage of `xrange` is that generated object will always take the same amount of memory.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] From version 2.2 forward, Python manifests lazy evaluation by implementing iterators (lazy sequences) unlike tuple or list sequences.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] , the first element '0' is printed when need arises.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] In the .NET framework, it is possible to do lazy evaluation using the class `System.Lazy<T>`.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] The class can be easily exploited in F# using the `lazy` keyword, while the `force` method will force the evaluation.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] There are also specialized collections like `Microsoft.FSharp.Collections.Seq` that provide built-in support for lazy evaluation.
[src:nix-language/lazy-evaluation] In C# and VB.NET, the class `System.Lazy<T>` is directly used.
[src:nix-language/manual-nix] Nix is a *purely functional package manager*.
[src:nix-language/manual-nix] This means that it treats packages like values in a purely functional programming language — packages are built by functions that don’t have side-effects, and they never change after they have been built.
[src:nix-language/manual-nix] where `b6gvzjyb2pg0…` is a unique identifier for the package that captures all its dependencies (it’s a cryptographic hash of the package’s build dependency graph).
[src:nix-language/manual-nix] You can have multiple versions or variants of a package installed at the same time.
[src:nix-language/manual-nix] This is especially important when different applications have dependencies on different versions of the same package — it prevents the “DLL hell”.
[src:nix-language/manual-nix] Because of the hashing scheme, different versions of a package end up in different paths in the Nix store, so they don’t interfere with each other.
[src:nix-language/manual-nix] An important consequence is that operations like upgrading or uninstalling an application cannot break other applications, since these operations never “destructively” update or delete files that are used by other packages.
[src:nix-language/manual-nix] Nix helps you make sure that package dependency specifications are complete.
[src:nix-language/manual-nix] In general, when you’re making a package for a package management system like RPM, you have to specify for each package what its dependencies are, but there are no guarantees that this specification is complete.
[src:nix-language/manual-nix] If you forget a dependency, then the package will build and work correctly on *your* machine if you have the dependency installed, but not on the end user's machine if it's not there.
[src:nix-language/manual-nix] Since Nix on the other hand doesn’t install packages in “global” locations like `/usr/bin` but in package-specific directories, the risk of incomplete dependencies is greatly reduced.
[src:nix-language/manual-nix] This is because tools such as compilers don’t search in per-packages directories such as `/nix/store/5lbfaxb722zp…-openssl-0.9.8d/include`, so if a package builds correctly on your system, this is because you specified the dependency explicitly.
[src:nix-language/manual-nix] This takes care of the build-time dependencies.
[src:nix-language/manual-nix] Once a package is built, runtime dependencies are found by scanning binaries for the hash parts of Nix store paths (such as `r8vvq9kq…`).
[src:nix-language/manual-nix] This sounds risky, but it works extremely well.
[src:nix-language/manual-nix] This means that non-privileged users can securely install software.
[src:nix-language/manual-nix] Each user can have a different *profile*, a set of packages in the Nix store that appear in the user’s `PATH`.
[src:nix-language/manual-nix] If a user installs a package that another user has already installed previously, the package won’t be built or downloaded a second time.
[src:nix-language/manual-nix] At the same time, it is not possible for one user to inject a Trojan horse into a package that might be used by another user.
[src:nix-language/manual-nix] Since package management operations never overwrite packages in the Nix store but just add new versions in different paths, they are *atomic*.
[src:nix-language/manual-nix] So during a package upgrade, there is no time window in which the package has some files from the old version and some files from the new version — which would be bad because a program might well crash if it’s started during that period.
[src:nix-language/manual-nix] And since packages aren’t overwritten, the old versions are still there after an upgrade.
[src:nix-language/manual-nix] the package isn’t deleted from the system right away (after all, you might want to do a rollback, or it might be in the profiles of other users).
[src:nix-language/manual-nix] This deletes all packages that aren’t in use by any user profile or by a currently running program.
[src:nix-language/manual-nix] Packages are built from *Nix expressions*, which is a simple functional language.
[src:nix-language/manual-nix] A Nix expression describes everything that goes into a package build task (a “derivation”): other packages, sources, the build script, environment variables for the build script, etc.
[src:nix-language/manual-nix] Nix tries very hard to ensure that Nix expressions are *deterministic*: building a Nix expression twice should yield the same result.
[src:nix-language/manual-nix] Because it’s a functional language, it’s easy to support building variants of a package: turn the Nix expression into a function and call it any number of times with the appropriate arguments.
[src:nix-language/manual-nix] Due to the hashing scheme, variants don’t conflict with each other in the Nix store.
[src:nix-language/manual-nix] We provide a large set of Nix expressions containing hundreds of existing Unix packages, the *Nix Packages collection* (Nixpkgs).
[src:nix-language/manual-nix] Nix is extremely useful for developers as it makes it easy to automatically set up the build environment for a package.
[src:nix-language/manual-nix] Given a Nix expression that describes the dependencies of your package, the command `nix-shell` will build or download those dependencies if they’re not already in your Nix store, and then start a Bash shell in which all necessary environment variables (such as compiler search paths) are set.
[src:nix-language/manual-nix] NixOS is a Linux distribution based on Nix.
[src:nix-language/manual-nix] It uses Nix not just for package management but also to manage the system configuration (e.g., to build configuration files in `/etc`).
[src:nix-language/manual-nix] This means, among other things, that it is easy to roll back the entire configuration of the system to an earlier state.
[src:nix-language/manual-nix] Also, users can install software without root privileges.
[src:nix-language/manual-nix] For more information and downloads, see the NixOS homepage.
[src:nix-language/manual-nix] Nix is released under the terms of the GNU LGPLv2.1 or (at your option) any later version.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] The Nix Packages collection (Nixpkgs) is a set of thousands of packages for the Nix package manager, released under a permissive MIT license.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Packages are available for several platforms, and can be used with the Nix package manager on most GNU/Linux distributions as well as NixOS.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] This document is the user *reference* manual for Nixpkgs.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] It describes the entire public interface of Nixpkgs in a concise and orderly manner, and all relevant behaviors, with examples and cross-references.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Nix expressions describe how to build packages from source and are collected in the Nixpkgs repository.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Also included in the collection are Nix expressions for NixOS modules.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] With these expressions the Nix package manager can build binary packages.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Packages, including the Nix packages collection, are distributed through channels.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] The collection is distributed for users of Nix on non-NixOS distributions through the channel `nixpkgs-unstable`.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Users of NixOS generally use one of the `nixos-*` channels, e.g., `nixos-22.11`, which includes all packages and modules for the stable NixOS 22.11.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Stable NixOS releases are generally only given security updates.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] More up-to-date packages and modules are available via the `nixos-unstable` channel.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Both `nixos-unstable` and `nixpkgs-unstable` follow the `master` branch of the Nixpkgs repository, although both do lag the `master` branch by generally a couple of days.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Updates to a channel are distributed as soon as all tests for that channel pass, e.g., this table shows the status of tests for the `nixpkgs-unstable` channel.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] The tests are conducted by a cluster called Hydra, which also builds binary packages from the Nix expressions in Nixpkgs for `x86_64-linux`, `aarch64-linux`, `x86_64-darwin` and `aarch64-darwin`.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] The binaries are made available via a binary cache.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] The current Nix expressions of the channels are available in the Nixpkgs repository in branches that correspond to the channel names (e.g., `nixos-22.11-small`).
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Packages receive varying degrees of support, both in terms of maintainer attention and available computation resources for continuous integration (CI).
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] We have 7 defined tiers denoting how well supported each platform is.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Tier 1 platforms receive the highest level of support where problems can block updates, platform-specific patches are freely applied, and most packages are expected to work.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Tier 2 platforms are expected to remain functional with updates, receive platform-specific patches as needed, and have many packages built by Hydra with full ofBorg support.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Tier 3 platforms may receive non-intrusive platform-specific fixes, have native bootstrap tools available with cross-build toolchains in binary cache, but updates might break builds on these platforms.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Platform Tiers 4 through 7 indicate varying levels of minimal support going from receiving only limited fixes to platforms with no support, but a path to support.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Nix comes with certain defaults about which packages can and cannot be installed, based on a package’s metadata.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Each of these criteria can be altered in the Nixpkgs configuration.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] All this is checked during evaluation already, and the check includes any package that is evaluated.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] In particular, all build-time dependencies are checked.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] A user’s Nixpkgs configuration is stored in a user-specific configuration file located at `~/.config/nixpkgs/config.nix`.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Unfree software is not tested or built in Nixpkgs continuous integration, and therefore not cached.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Most unfree licenses prohibit either executing or distributing the software.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] The `NIXPKGS_CONFIG` environment variable can override the configuration file location.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] `~/.config/nixpkgs/config.nix`, if it exists.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] `~/.nixpkgs/config.nix` (legacy), if it exists.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] On NixOS, `NIXPKGS_CONFIG` points to `/etc/nix/nixpkgs-config.nix` system-wide.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Drop a file there to apply configuration to `nix-env`, `nix-shell`, and other user-level commands.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] The `nixpkgs.config` option does not affect `nix-env`, `nix-shell`, or other user-level commands.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] This lookup applies to non-flake usage like channels and `<nixpkgs>`.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Flakes ignore it; pass `config` directly when importing `nixpkgs`.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] There are several ways to try compiling a package which has been marked as broken.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] There are also two ways to try compiling a package which has been marked as unsupported for the given system.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] The difference between a package being unsupported on some system and being broken is admittedly a bit fuzzy.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] If a program *ought* to work on a certain platform, but doesn’t, the platform should be included in `meta.platforms`, but marked as broken with e.g.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] `meta.broken = !hostPlatform.isWindows`.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Of course, this begs the question of what “ought” means exactly.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] All users of Nixpkgs are free software users, and many users (and developers) of Nixpkgs want to limit and tightly control their exposure to unfree software.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] At the same time, many users need (or want) to run some specific pieces of proprietary software.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Nixpkgs includes some expressions for unfree software packages.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] By default unfree software cannot be installed and doesn’t show up in searches.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] There are several ways to tweak how Nix handles a package which has been marked as unfree.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] A complete list of licenses can be found in the file `lib/licenses.nix` of the nixpkgs tree.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] There are several ways to tweak how Nix handles a package which has been marked as insecure.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] A package may have several problems associated with it.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] These can be either manually declared in `meta.problems`, or automatically generated from its other `meta` attributes.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Each problem has a name, a “kind”, a message, and optionally a list of URLs.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Not all kinds can be manually specified in `meta.problems`, and some kinds can exist only up to once per package.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Each problem has a handler that deals with it, which can be one of “error”, “warn” or “ignore”. “error” will disallow evaluating a package, while “warn” will simply print a message to the log.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] The handler for problems can be specified using `config.problems.handlers.${packageName}.${problemName} = "${handler}";`.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] There is also the possibility to specify some generic matchers, which can set a handler for more than a specific problem of a specific package.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Matchers can match one or more of package name, problem name or problem kind.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] If multiple conditions are present, all must be met to match.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] If multiple matchers match a problem, then the highest severity handler will be chosen.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] The current default value contains `{ kind = "removal"; handler = "warn"; }`, meaning that people will be notified about package removals in advance.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Package names for both `problems.handlers` and `problems.matchers` are taken from `lib.getName`, which looks at the `pname` first and falls back to extracting the “pname” part from the `name` attribute.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] You can define a function called `packageOverrides` in your local `~/.config/nixpkgs/config.nix` to override Nix packages.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] It must be a function that takes pkgs as an argument and returns a modified set of packages.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] The following attributes can be passed in `config`.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Whether to set `enableParallelBuilding` to true by default while building nixpkgs packages.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Changing the default may cause a mass rebuild.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Whether to expose old attribute names for compatibility.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] The recommended setting is to enable this, as it improves backward compatibility, easing updates.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] The only reason to disable aliases is for continuous integration purposes.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] For instance, Nixpkgs should not depend on aliases in its internal code.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Projects that aren’t Nixpkgs should be cautious of instantly removing all usages of aliases, as migrating too soon can break compatibility with the stable Nixpkgs releases.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] See Installing broken packages in the NixOS manual.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Silence the warning for the upcoming deprecation of the `x86_64-darwin` platform in Nixpkgs 26.11.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] See the release notes for more information.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] See Installing unfree packages in the NixOS manual.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Allows specific unfree packages to be used.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] This option composes with `nixpkgs.config.allowUnfreePredicate` by also allowing the listed package names.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Unlike `nixpkgs.config.allowUnfreePredicate`, this option merges additively, similar to `environment.systemPackages`.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] This enables defining allowed unfree packages in multiple modules, close to where they are used.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] This avoids the need to centralize all unfree package declarations or globally enable unfree packages via `nixpkgs.config.allowUnfree = true`.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] See Installing packages on unsupported systems in the NixOS manual.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Variants are instances of the current nixpkgs instance with different stdenvs or other applied options.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] This allows for using different toolchains, libcs, or global build changes across nixpkgs.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Disabling can ensure nixpkgs is only building for the platform which you specified.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Whether to check that the `meta` attribute of derivations are correct during evaluation time.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Whether to set `configurePlatforms` to `["build" "host"]` by default while building nixpkgs packages.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Whether to set `__contentAddressed` to true by default while building nixpkgs packages.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] A list of CUDA capabilities to build for.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Packages may use this option to control device code generation to take advantage of architecture-specific functionality, speed up compile times by producing less device code, or slim package closures.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] For example, you can build for Ada Lovelace GPUs with `cudaCapabilities = [ "8.9" ];`.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] If not provided, the default value is calculated per-package set, derived from a list of GPUs supported by that CUDA version.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] See the CUDA section in the Nixpkgs manual for more information.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Whether to enable PTX support for future hardware.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] When enabled, packages will include PTX code that can be JIT-compiled for GPUs newer than those explicitly targeted by `cudaCapabilities`.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Whether to build packages with CUDA support by default while building nixpkgs packages.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Whether to run `checkPhase` by default while building nixpkgs packages.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] This controls the default derivation `name` attribute set by the `fetch*` (`fetchzip`, `fetchFromGitHub`, etc) functions.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] The default `"source"` is the best choice for minimal rebuilds, it will ignore any non-hash changes (like branches being renamed, source URLs changing, etc) at the cost of `/nix/store` being easily cache-poisoned (see NixOS/nix#969).
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Setting this to `"versioned"` greatly helps with discoverability of sources in `/nix/store` and makes cache-poisoning of `/nix/store` much harder, at the cost of a single mass-rebuild for all `src` derivations, and an occasional rebuild when a source changes some of its non-hash attributes.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Setting this to `"full"` is similar to setting it to `"versioned"`, but the use of `fetcherName` in the derivation name will force a rebuild when `src` switches between `fetch*` functions, thus forcing `nix` to check new derivation’s `outputHash`, which is useful for debugging.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Also, `"full"` is useful for easy collection and tracking of statistics of where the packages you use are hosted.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] If you are a developer, you should probably set this to at least`"versioned"`.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Changing the default will cause a mass rebuild.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] The default git configuration for all `pkgs.fetchgit` calls.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Among many other potential uses, this can be used to override URLs to point to local mirrors.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Changing this will not cause any rebuilds because `pkgs.fetchgit` produces a fixed-output derivation.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] To set the configuration file directly, use the `gitConfigFile` option instead.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] To set the configuration file for individual calls, use `fetchgit { gitConfigFile = "..."; }`.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] A path to a git configuration file, to be used for all `pkgs.fetchgit` calls.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] This overrides the `gitConfig` option, see its documentation for more details.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] The set of content-addressed/hashed mirror URLs used by `pkgs.fetchurl`.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] In case `pkgs.fetchurl` can’t download from the given URLs, it will try the hashed mirrors based on the expected output hash.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] See `copy-tarballs.pl` for more details on how hashed mirrors are constructed.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] If the Microsoft Visual Studio license has been accepted.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Please read https://www.visualstudio.com/license-terms/mt644918/ and enable this config if you accept.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] The default npm registry overrides for all `fetchNpmDeps` calls, as an attribute set.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] For each attribute, all files fetched from the host corresponding to the name will instead be fetched from the host (and sub-path) specified in the value.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] For example, an override like `"registry.npmjs.org" = "my-mirror.local/registry.npmjs.org"` will replace a URL like `https://registry.npmjs.org/foo.tar.gz` with `https://my-mirror.local/registry.npmjs.org/foo.tar.gz`.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] To set the string directly, see `npmRegistryOverridesString`.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] A string containing a string with a JSON representation of npm registry overrides for `fetchNpmDeps`.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] This overrides the `npmRegistryOverrides` option, see its documentation for more details.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Specify how to handle packages with problems.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Each key has the format `packageName.problemName`, each value is one of “error”, “warn” or “ignore”.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] This option takes precedence over anything in `problems.matchers`.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Package names are taken from `lib.getName`, which looks at the `pname` first and falls back to extracting the “pname” part from the `name` attribute.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] See <link xlink:href=“https://nixos.org/manual/nixpkgs/stable/#sec-ignore-problems”>Installing packages with problems</link> in the NixOS manual.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] A more powerful and less ergonomic version of `problems.handlers`.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Each value is a matcher, that may match onto certain properties of a problem and specify a handler for them.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] If multiple matchers match a problem, the handler with the highest severity (error > warn > ignore) will be used.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Values in `problems.handlers` always take precedence over matchers.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Any matchers must not contain both a `package` and `name` field, for this should be handled by using `problems.handlers` instead.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] In which way to recurse through Nixpkgs.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] In most cases you want keep this as the default.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] You can use this to emulate how `hydra` and `search` are going through Nixpkgs.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Use the bootstrap files returned instead of the default bootstrap files.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] The default bootstrap files are passed as an argument.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] A function to replace the standard environment (stdenv).
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] The function receives an attribute set with `pkgs` and should return a stdenv derivation.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] This can be used to globally replace the stdenv with a custom one, for example to use ccache or distcc.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] A hook to rewrite/filter URLs before they are fetched.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] The function is passed the URL as a string, and is expected to return a new URL, or null if the given URL should not be attempted.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] This function is applied *prior* to resolving mirror:// URLs.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] The intended use is to allow URL rewriting to insert company-internal mirrors, or work around company firewalls and similar network restrictions.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Whether to build packages with ROCm support by default while building nixpkgs packages.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Which warnings to display for potentially dangerous or deprecated values passed into `stdenv.mkDerivation`.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] A list of warnings can be found in /pkgs/stdenv/generic/check-meta.nix.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] This is not a stable interface; warnings may be added, changed or removed without prior notice.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Whether to set `strictDeps` to true by default while building nixpkgs packages.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Whether to set `__structuredAttrs` to true by default while building nixpkgs packages.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Whether to warn when `config` contains an unrecognized attribute.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Using `packageOverrides`, it is possible to manage packages declaratively.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] This means that we can list all of our desired packages within a declarative Nix expression.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] To install it into our environment, you can just run `nix-env -iA nixpkgs.myPackages`.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] If you want to load the packages to be built from a working copy of `nixpkgs` you just run `nix-env -f. -iA myPackages`.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] To explore what’s been installed, just look through `~/.nix-profile/`.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] You can see that a lot of stuff has been installed.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Some of this stuff is useful some of it isn’t.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] `pathsToLink` tells Nixpkgs to only link the paths listed which gets rid of the extra stuff in the profile.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] `/bin` and `/share` are good defaults for a user environment, getting rid of the clutter.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] If you are running on Nix on macOS, you may want to add another path as well, `/Applications`, that makes GUI apps available.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] After building that new environment, look through `~/.nix-profile` to make sure everything is there that we wanted.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Discerning readers will note that some files are missing.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Look inside `~/.nix-profile/share/man/man1/` to verify this.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] There are no man pages for any of the Nix tools!
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] This is because some packages like Nix have multiple outputs for things like documentation (see section 4).
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] This provides us with some useful documentation for using our packages.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] However, if we actually want those manpages to be detected by man, we need to set up our environment.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] This can also be managed within Nix expressions.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] For this to work fully, you must also have this script sourced when you are logged in.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] "${HOME}/.profile"` and you can start loading man pages from your environment.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Configuring GNU info is a little bit trickier than man pages.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] To work correctly, info needs a database to be generated.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] This can be done with some small modifications to our environment scripts.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] `postBuild` tells Nixpkgs to run a command after building the environment.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] In this case, `install-info` adds the installed info pages to `dir` which is GNU info’s default root node.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Note that `texinfoInteractive` is added to the environment to give the `install-info` command.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] This chapter describes how to extend and change Nixpkgs using overlays.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Overlays are used to add layers in the fixed-point used by Nixpkgs to compose the set of all packages.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Nixpkgs can be configured with a list of overlays, which are applied in order.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] This means that the order of the overlays can be significant if multiple layers override the same package.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] The list of overlays can be set either explicitly in a Nix expression, or through `<nixpkgs-overlays>` or user configuration files.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] On a NixOS system the value of the `nixpkgs.overlays` option, if present, is passed to the system Nixpkgs directly as an argument.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Note that this does not affect the overlays for non-NixOS operations (e.g.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] `nix-env`), which are looked up independently.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] The list of overlays can be passed explicitly when importing nixpkgs, for example `import <nixpkgs> { overlays = [ overlay1 overlay2 ]; }`.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Further overlays can be added by calling the `pkgs.extend` or `pkgs.appendOverlays`, although it is often preferable to avoid these functions, because they recompute the Nixpkgs fixpoint, which is somewhat expensive to do.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] The list of overlays is determined as follows.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] If one of `~/.config/nixpkgs/overlays.nix` and `~/.config/nixpkgs/overlays/` exists, then we look for overlays at that path, as described below.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Overlays are Nix functions which accept two arguments, conventionally called either `final` and `prev` in newer code or `self` and `super` in older code, and return a set of packages.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] For example, the following is a valid overlay.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] The first argument (`final`, `self`) corresponds to the final package set.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] You should use this set for the dependencies of all packages specified in your overlay.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] For example, all the dependencies of `rr` in the example above come from `final`, as well as the overridden dependencies used in the `boost` override.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] The second argument (`prev`, `super`) corresponds to the result of the evaluation of the previous stages of Nixpkgs.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] It does not contain any of the packages added by the current overlay, nor any of the following overlays.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] This set should be used either to refer to packages you wish to override, or to access functions defined in Nixpkgs.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] For example, the original recipe of `boost` in the above example, comes from `prev`, as well as the `callPackage` function.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] The value returned by this function should be a set similar to `pkgs/top-level/all-packages.nix`, containing overridden and/or new packages.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Overlays are similar to other methods for customizing Nixpkgs, in particular the `packageOverrides` attribute described in the section called “Modify packages via `packageOverrides`”.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] Indeed, `packageOverrides` acts as an overlay with only the `prev` argument.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p01] It is therefore appropriate for basic use, but overlays are more powerful and easier to distribute.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] Certain software packages have different implementations of the same interface.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] Other distributions have functionality to switch between these.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] For example, Debian provides DebianAlternatives.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] Nixpkgs has what we call `alternatives`, which are configured through overlays.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] In Nixpkgs, we have multiple implementations of the BLAS/LAPACK numerical linear algebra interfaces.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] Introduced in PR #83888, we are able to override the `blas` and `lapack` packages to use different implementations, through the `blasProvider` and `lapackProvider` argument.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] This can be used to select a different provider.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] BLAS providers will have symlinks in `$out/lib/libblas.so.3` and `$out/lib/libcblas.so.3` to their respective BLAS libraries.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] Likewise, LAPACK providers will have symlinks in `$out/lib/liblapack.so.3` and `$out/lib/liblapacke.so.3` to their respective LAPACK libraries.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] For example, Intel MKL is both a BLAS and LAPACK provider.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] This overlay uses Intel’s MKL library for both BLAS and LAPACK interfaces.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] Note that the same can be accomplished at runtime using `LD_LIBRARY_PATH` of `libblas.so.3` and `liblapack.so.3`.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] Intel MKL requires an `openmp` implementation when running with multiple processors.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] By default, `mkl` will use Intel’s `iomp` implementation if no other is specified, but this is a runtime-only dependency and binary compatible with the LLVM implementation.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] To use that one instead, Intel recommends users set it with `LD_PRELOAD`.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] Note that `mkl` is only available on `x86_64-linux` and `x86_64-darwin`.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] Moreover, Hydra is not building and distributing pre-compiled binaries using it.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] For BLAS/LAPACK switching to work correctly, all packages must depend on `blas` or `lapack`.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] This ensures that only one BLAS/LAPACK library is used at one time.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] There are two versions of BLAS/LAPACK currently in the wild, `LP64` (integer size = 32 bits) and `ILP64` (integer size = 64 bits).
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] The attributes `blas` and `lapack` are `LP64` by default.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] Their `ILP64` version are provided through the attributes `blas-ilp64` and `lapack-ilp64`.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] Some software needs special flags or patches to work with `ILP64`.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] You can check if `ILP64` is used in Nixpkgs with `blas.isILP64` and `lapack.isILP64`.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] Some software does NOT work with `ILP64`, and derivations need to specify an assertion to prevent this.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] All programs that are built with MPI support use the generic attribute `mpi` as an input.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] Sometimes one wants to override parts of `nixpkgs`, e.g. derivation attributes, the results of derivations.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] These functions are used to make changes to packages, returning only single packages.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] Overlays, on the other hand, can be used to combine the overridden packages across the entire package set of Nixpkgs.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] The function `override` is usually available for all the derivations in the nixpkgs expression (`pkgs`).
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] It is used to override the arguments passed to a function.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] It’s also possible to access the previous arguments.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] In the first example, `pkgs.foo` is the result of a function call with some default arguments, usually a derivation.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] Using `pkgs.foo.override` will call the same function with the given new arguments.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] Many packages, like the `foo` example above, provide package options with default values in their arguments, to facilitate overriding.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] Because it’s not usually feasible to test that packages build with all combinations of options, you might find that a package doesn’t build if you override options to non-default values.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] Package maintainers are not expected to fix arbitrary combinations of options.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] If you find that something doesn’t work, please submit a fix, ideally with a regression test.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] If you want to ensure that things keep working, consider becoming a maintainer for the package.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] The function `overrideAttrs` allows overriding the attribute set passed to a `stdenv.mkDerivation` call, producing a new derivation based on the original one.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] This function is available on all derivations produced by the `stdenv.mkDerivation` function, which is most packages in the Nixpkgs expression `pkgs`.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] In the above example, “-bar” is appended to the pname attribute, while all other attributes will be retained from the original `hello` package.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] The argument `previousAttrs` is conventionally used to refer to the attr set originally passed to `stdenv.mkDerivation`.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] The argument `finalAttrs` refers to the final attributes passed to `mkDerivation`, plus the `finalPackage` attribute which is equal to the result of `mkDerivation` or subsequent `overrideAttrs` calls.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] If only a one-argument function is written, the argument has the meaning of `previousAttrs`.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] Function arguments can be omitted entirely if there is no need to access `previousAttrs` or `finalAttrs`.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] In the above example, the `separateDebugInfo` attribute is overridden to be true, thus building debug info for `helloWithDebug`.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] Note that `separateDebugInfo` is processed only by the `stdenv.mkDerivation` function, not the generated, raw Nix derivation.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] Thus, using `overrideDerivation` will not work in this case, as it overrides only the attributes of the final derivation.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] `buildInputs` vs `nativeBuildInputs`), and it involves less typing).
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] You should prefer `overrideAttrs` in almost all cases, see its documentation for the reasons why.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] `overrideDerivation` is not deprecated and will continue to work, but is less nice to use and does not have as many abilities as `overrideAttrs`.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] Do not use this function in Nixpkgs as it evaluates a derivation before modifying it, which breaks package abstraction.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] In addition, this evaluation-per-function application incurs a performance penalty, which can become a problem if many overrides are used.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] It is only intended for ad-hoc customisation, such as in `~/.config/nixpkgs/config.nix`.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] The function `overrideDerivation` creates a new derivation based on an existing one by overriding the original’s attributes with the attribute set produced by the specified function.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] This function is available on all derivations defined using the `makeOverridable` function.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] Most standard derivation-producing functions, such as `stdenv.mkDerivation`, are defined using this function, which means most packages in the Nixpkgs expression, `pkgs`, have this function.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] In the above example, the `name`, `src`, and `patches` of the derivation will be overridden, while all other attributes will be retained from the original derivation.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] The argument `oldAttrs` is used to refer to the attribute set of the original derivation.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] A package’s attributes are evaluated *before* being modified by the `overrideDerivation` function.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] For example, the `name` attribute reference in `url = "mirror://gnu/hello/${name}.tar.gz";` is filled-in *before* the `overrideDerivation` function modifies the attribute set.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] This means that overriding the `name` attribute, in this example, *will not* change the value of the `url` attribute.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] Instead, we need to override both the `name` *and* `url` attributes.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] The function `lib.makeOverridable` is used to make the result of a function easily customizable.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] This utility only makes sense for functions that accept an argument set and return an attribute set.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] The variable `c` is the value of the `f` function applied with some default arguments.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] Hence the value of `c.result` is `3`, in this example.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] The variable `c` however also has some additional functions, like c.override which can be used to override the default arguments.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p02] In this example the value of `(c.override { a = 4; }).result` is 6.
