[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p04] `fix f` computes the fixed point of the given function `f`.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p04] In other words, the return value is `x` in `x = f x`.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p04] This means that `x` must be a value that can be partially evaluated, such as an attribute set, a list, or a function.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p04] This way, `f` can use one part of `x` to compute another part.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p04] This section explains `fix` by refactoring from syntactic recursion to a call of `fix` instead.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p04] For context, Nix lets you define attributes in terms of other attributes syntactically using the `rec { }` syntax.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p04] But in general you can get more reuse out of `let` bindings by refactoring them to a function.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p04] This is where `fix` comes in, it contains the syntactic recursion that’s not in `f` anymore.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p04] By applying `fix` we get the final result.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p04] Such a refactored `f` using `fix` is not useful by itself.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p04] There `self` is also often called `final`.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p04] Located at lib/fixed-points.nix:92 in `<nixpkgs>`.
