[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p05] Creates an Option attribute set for an option that specifies the package a module should use for some purpose.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p05] The package is specified in the third argument under `default` as a list of strings representing its attribute path in nixpkgs (or another package set).
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p05] Because of this, you need to pass nixpkgs itself (usually `pkgs` in a module; alternatively to nixpkgs itself, another package set) as the first argument.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p05] If you pass another package set you should set the `pkgsText` option.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p05] This option is used to display the expression for the package set.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p05] If your expression is complex you should parenthesize it, as the `pkgsText` argument is usually immediately followed by an attribute lookup (`.`).
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p05] The second argument may be either a string or a list of strings.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p05] It provides the display name of the package in the description of the generated option (using only the last element if the passed value is a list) and serves as the fallback value for the `default` argument.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p05] To include extra information in the description, pass `extraDescription` to append arbitrary text to the generated description.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p05] You can also pass an `example` value, either a literal string or an attribute path.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p05] The `default` argument can be omitted if the provided name is an attribute of pkgs (if `name` is a string) or a valid attribute path in pkgs (if `name` is a list).
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p05] You can also set `default` to just a string in which case it is interpreted as an attribute name (a singleton attribute path, if you will).
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p05] If you wish to explicitly provide no default, pass `null` as `default`.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p05] If you want users to be able to set no package, pass `nullable = true`.
[src:nix-language/manual-nixpkgs-p05] In this mode a `default = null` will not be interpreted as no default and is interpreted literally.
